				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(\text {C}_6\text {H}_{10}\text {O}_5)$$\end{document} is the most abundant species in bio-oil, which is obtained mostly from the conversion of cellulose (Rabinovich et al. 2009). The average molecular weight of the bio-oil is seen to increase with the amount of lignin in the feedstock, since the resulting vapour contains heavier compounds (Fahmi et al. 2008).

Based on the operating conditions, pyrolysis can be categorised as either slow, fast or flash pyrolysis. Slow pyrolysis is characterised by slow heating rates 0.1-1∘Cs-1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\left( {0.1}{-}{1}\,^\circ \text {C s}^{-1}\right) $$\end{document} and long particle and vapour residence times 450-550s\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\left( {450}{-}{550}\text {s} \right) $$\end{document}. These conditions promote the devolitilisation to occur in favour of the char residue. Also, if the residence time is long, then the produced vapour will inevitably partake in secondary decomposition reactions, further reducing the yield of pyrolysis-oil. On the contrary, fast pyrolysis requires much faster heating rates 10-100∘Cs-1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\left( {10}{-}{100}\,^\circ \text {C s}^{-1} \right) $$\end{document}, and the residence time 0.5-10s\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\left( {0.5}{-}{10}\text {s} \right) $$\end{document} of particles and the liberated vapour is minimised by employing rapid gas flow rates. In this heating regime, the devolatilisation produces more condensable vapours. Due to their rapid release from the reactor, these vapours are largely prevented from further decomposition. The flash pyrolysis features even faster heating >1000∘C-1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
