				\begin{document}$$P = P(t)$$\end{document}. In this case, the mechanical pressure p in Eq. (2) remains distinct from P and takes on the role of a kinematic variable akin to a multiplier that enforces the continuity equation (Eq. (1)). In reactors that are open to the environment or that are operated at constant pressure by means of a movable piston, P is prescribed as the ambient pressure. If a reactor is operated at a prescribed volume V(t), by contrast, P can be computed in terms of the total reactor volume from Eq. (4). Physically, the assumption that the thermodynamic pressure P is homogeneous and independent of p is associated with a low Mach number, Ma≲0.3\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
