In pyrolysis, the change of particle mass is controlled by two phenomena, drying and devolatilisation. Drying describes the evaporation of contained liquid water and requires the supply of heat through exothermal intra-particle reactions or by external heat transfer from the ambience. Devolatilisaion, by contrast, is the process of liberation of gaseous species from particles, produced as a result of the thermal decomposition of the feedstock. In the following, we denote the rates of drying and devolatilisation by m˙jevap\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
