Conduction describes the heat transfer through direct contact from an element of high temperature to another at a lower temperature, without an apparent motion of matter. In fluids, this is facilitated by collisions and diffusion at the molecular level, whereas in solids, it proceeds through lattice vibrations and the movement of free electrons. The conduction in the gas phase is accounted for by the third term on the right hand side of Eq.  (16), and needs no further detailing. On the other hand, the interparticle conductive term Q˙jcond\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
