As mentioned in Sect. 2.2 above, the flow of gas is commonly assumed to leave the angular momentum of a particle unaffected. However, the gas flow influences the linear momentum of a particle via two distinct forces, the buoyancy force and drag. The buoyancy force Fjb\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
